00:10:45,788 --> 00:10:48,330
And I've been to Holland, and I didn't see that.

243
00:10:50,262 --> 00:10:52,044
But anyway, going back to Drake's for a second.

244
00:10:52,044 --> 00:10:54,026
The really interesting term in here,

245
00:10:54,026 --> 00:10:56,248
the one that we know probably the least about,

246
00:10:56,248 --> 00:10:57,289
is the probability of life occurring.

247
00:10:57,289 --> 00:10:59,671
What is the chance life can spontaneously arise somewhere?

248
00:10:59,671 --> 00:11:02,954
So then that drove me down a totally different direction,

249
00:11:02,954 --> 00:11:03,335
the origin of life.

250
00:11:03,335 --> 00:11:05,417
And there are all these convoluted theories

251
00:11:05,417 --> 00:11:08,059
about how life might have started.

252
00:11:08,059 --> 00:11:10,882
They basically usually resolve down to this.

253
00:11:10,882 --> 00:11:10,942
But...

254
00:11:12,510 --> 00:11:14,011
Then we looked into it.

255
00:11:14,011 --> 00:11:16,573
And this really was part of the powers of 10 thing.

256
00:11:16,573 --> 00:11:18,274
It was drawing us down into the microscopic world here.

257
00:11:18,274 --> 00:11:21,077
And so I thought, okay, initially this is kind of a space thing.

258
00:11:21,077 --> 00:11:22,618
Maybe it's a microscopic thing too.

259
00:11:22,618 --> 00:11:28,002
Now, a little bit of overview here.

260
00:11:28,002 --> 00:11:31,705
14 million years ago, billion years ago, big bang, and here we are now.

261
00:11:32,170 --> 00:11:34,612
The Earth remarkably formed about 4 billion years ago,

262
00:11:34,612 --> 00:11:37,313
which is a significant fraction of the age of the known universe.

263
00:11:37,313 --> 00:11:40,816
And the fact that the Earth has remained fairly stable over that period of time is pretty remarkable.

264
00:11:40,816 --> 00:11:45,458
Another remarkable thing is that evidence of life on Earth was very soon after the Earth formed.

265
00:11:45,458 --> 00:11:47,640
And they're still trying to refine that.

266
00:11:47,640 --> 00:11:50,401
Every time they find an older one, it gets a little bit closer and a little bit closer

267
00:11:50,401 --> 00:11:51,722
to the time when the Earth finally cooled off.

268
00:11:52,392 --> 00:11:58,274
Now, we see that it took about 2 billion years for life to go from very primitive prokaryotic

269
00:11:58,274 --> 00:12:02,536
microbes to more advanced eukaryotic microbes, and another 1.5 billion years to get to what

270
00:12:02,536 --> 00:12:08,339
we consider kind of macroscopic interesting life. So, it was about 3 billion years before

271
00:12:08,339 --> 00:12:13,182
life, you know, got kind of large, multicellular. And it's only been that for about 500 million

272
00:12:13,182 --> 00:12:14,022
years so far.

273
00:12:14,778 --> 00:12:19,161
One of the early trips I took researching spore was to the Scripps Institute down in La Jolla

274
00:12:19,161 --> 00:12:24,104
and met this guy, Stan Miller, who back in the 50s did the very first origin of life experiments

275
00:12:24,104 --> 00:12:28,026
where he would take these flasks, fill them with, like, you know, methane and spark them

276
00:12:28,026 --> 00:12:29,086
and see what would come out of it.

277
00:12:29,086 --> 00:12:32,048
You know, he was trying to recreate the early prebiotic atmosphere of the Earth

278
00:12:32,048 --> 00:12:34,129
and he actually was creating amino acids

279
00:12:34,129 --> 00:12:37,951
and it was the first kind of idea that maybe this stuff could have arisen naturally, these chemicals.

280
00:12:37,951 --> 00:12:41,153
One of my prized possessions is this that he gave me

281
00:12:41,153 --> 00:12:43,174
that he actually signs, it says Stan Miller.

282
00:12:43,234 --> 00:12:44,955
It's like sitting on a shelf in my house.

283
00:12:44,955 --> 00:12:47,057
Every now and then, somebody will come and say,

284
00:12:47,057 --> 00:12:48,318
Oh, you should throw this out. It's ruined.

285
00:12:48,318 --> 00:12:48,978
And I was like, No!

286
00:12:48,978 --> 00:12:51,960
I also met David Brin down there,

287
00:12:51,960 --> 00:12:54,262
who's one of my favorite science fiction authors.

288
00:12:54,262 --> 00:12:56,624
One of his best-known series is the Uplift series,

289
00:12:56,624 --> 00:12:58,645
which is a concept that we kind of, you know,

290
00:12:58,645 --> 00:13:00,006
are bringing into Spore, where you can kind of

291
00:13:00,006 --> 00:13:02,288
uplift unintelligent animals to intelligence.

292
00:13:02,288 --> 00:13:05,170
In describing Spore to him, he basically said,

293
00:13:05,170 --> 00:13:07,231
Oh, it sounds cool, but I want this game.

294
00:13:07,231 --> 00:13:09,133
I want the game where I can change the fundamental

295
00:13:09,133 --> 00:13:12,915
consonants of the universe and see what emerges.

296
00:13:12,915 --> 00:13:12,995
And...

297
00:13:13,447 --> 00:13:17,909
Aside from being kind of a difficult thing to do, even in comparison to Spore,

