357
00:16:02,369 --> 00:16:04,570
And, of course, nuclear reactors don't really do that.

358
00:16:04,570 --> 00:16:05,811
But, you know, a lot of times in games,

359
00:16:05,811 --> 00:16:07,952
we will purposely basically break reality

360
00:16:07,952 --> 00:16:08,813
for the player expectation.

361
00:16:09,662 --> 00:16:10,863
I'm not against that at all.

362
00:16:10,863 --> 00:16:14,546
In fact, I think, you know, fiction is a very interesting way to kind of approach reality.

363
00:16:14,546 --> 00:16:18,068
One thing that Rod Sterling said when he was doing the Twilight Zone,

364
00:16:18,068 --> 00:16:21,690
he said that was the only place in television where he could do real issues.

365
00:16:21,690 --> 00:16:24,612
And this is back in the late 50s when he started the Twilight Zone.

366
00:16:24,612 --> 00:16:28,675
And he could actually do things about gender equality or racial issues.

367
00:16:28,975 --> 00:16:31,416
by making, you know, one guy an alien and one guy an earthling.

368
00:16:31,416 --> 00:16:33,858
Where at that time on TV, if they tried to deal with these racial issues

369
00:16:33,858 --> 00:16:36,240
with blacks and whites, they would never get it on the air.

370
00:16:36,240 --> 00:16:38,421
So it was a way for him to get a message out there

371
00:16:38,421 --> 00:16:40,242
that at the time was very hard to get out.

372
00:16:40,242 --> 00:16:42,724
As far back as Mary Shelley writing Frankenstein,

373
00:16:42,724 --> 00:16:45,986
you know, she had a very deep message embedded in this work of fiction,

374
00:16:45,986 --> 00:16:47,807
you know, that she was hoping to have some impact on society.

375
00:16:47,807 --> 00:16:51,690
So really, you know, in some sense, I wanted to interact

376
00:16:51,690 --> 00:16:54,032
with lots of interesting aliens in this game.

377
00:16:54,457 --> 00:16:57,499
And the idea of having to deal with protein folding and cellular metabolism

378
00:16:57,499 --> 00:16:59,260
was kind of a little bit at odds with that.

379
00:16:59,260 --> 00:17:01,041
And, you know, you'll see a little bit later

380
00:17:01,041 --> 00:17:02,782
kind of how we fell on the side of the fence,

381
00:17:02,782 --> 00:17:05,523
you know, which side of the fence we fell on different issues.

382
00:17:05,523 --> 00:17:08,225
A lot of times in research, you know, we'll start doing prototypes.

383
00:17:08,225 --> 00:17:11,586
I don't know if any of you all saw the excellent prototyping talk this morning

384
00:17:11,586 --> 00:17:12,767
by Hayim and Chris.

385
00:17:12,767 --> 00:17:14,148
Yeah, it was a great talk.

386
00:17:15,350 --> 00:17:17,950
And as I was mentioning, you know, we do a lot of simulation prototypes.

387
00:17:17,950 --> 00:17:20,151
You know, the very best ones, we will actually kind of bring

388
00:17:20,151 --> 00:17:21,471
to more extensive gameplay prototypes.

389
00:17:21,471 --> 00:17:24,211
Originally, we were just simulating dynamics of a simple system,

