00:21:15,245 --> 00:21:18,829
So, and it could have been almost, you know,

480
00:21:18,829 --> 00:21:21,431
this talk almost was about robots instead of aliens,

481
00:21:21,431 --> 00:21:24,875
because aliens and robots to me represent, you know, very similar things.

482
00:21:24,875 --> 00:21:27,798
You know, they kind of represent views of humanity.

483
00:21:27,935 --> 00:21:32,498
You don't really realize how amazing the human hand is until you try to build one.

484
00:21:32,498 --> 00:21:37,421
Once you try to build one, you go back and look at this and the dexterity and the strength and the flexibility.

485
00:21:37,421 --> 00:21:40,904
It's just an amazing, amazing thing.

486
00:21:40,904 --> 00:21:47,329
So in some sense, robots give us a better understanding of who we are and, you know, what makes us tick.

487
00:21:47,329 --> 00:21:50,131
Now, you're going to hear me talk about this movie a lot.

488
00:21:50,131 --> 00:21:51,371
My favorite movie of all time, 2001.

489
00:21:51,371 --> 00:21:53,293
I'm completely operational and all my circuits are functioning perfectly.

490
00:21:53,575 --> 00:21:55,957
So when I was 7 years old, I saw this movie and I met Hal

491
00:21:55,957 --> 00:21:57,378
and it had a deep impact on me.

492
00:21:57,378 --> 00:21:58,899
You know, the idea that there could be this machine

493
00:21:58,899 --> 00:22:01,641
that thought like a person and you could interact with.

494
00:22:01,641 --> 00:22:04,063
And it just fundamentally, you know, just blew me away as a kid.

495
00:22:04,063 --> 00:22:07,466
What's interesting is, you know, people saw that movie

496
00:22:07,466 --> 00:22:09,007
and they came out and, you know,

497
00:22:09,007 --> 00:22:10,928
this is right at the dawn of AI, really, right?

498
00:22:10,928 --> 00:22:13,891
And they were amazed that a computer could beat this guy at chess.

499
00:22:13,891 --> 00:22:16,533
And they weren't amazed at all that he could have these conversations,

500
00:22:16,533 --> 00:22:18,214
do all this common sense reasoning, you know.

501
00:22:19,522 --> 00:22:22,064
And that was a very interesting insight into human intelligence.

502
00:22:22,064 --> 00:22:25,247
You know, because we had thought of, you know, playing chess as being, you know,

503
00:22:25,247 --> 00:22:26,788
something that required a lot of intelligence,

504
00:22:26,788 --> 00:22:28,409
and tying your shoes as being simple.

505
00:22:28,409 --> 00:22:29,750
And we're finding out that's not the case.

506
00:22:29,750 --> 00:22:33,314
You know, and we found that out through trying to recreate those abilities in machines.

507
00:22:33,314 --> 00:22:35,435
Um, you know, the lip-reading stuff he did.

508
00:22:35,435 --> 00:22:37,597
Uh, so in some sense, um,

509
00:22:37,597 --> 00:22:42,201
aliens and robots both represent kind of boundaries or aspects of humanity.

510
00:22:42,201 --> 00:22:44,964
Uh, you know, we have, you know, nice aliens, friendly aliens.

511
00:22:44,964 --> 00:22:47,546
We have really mean, scary, you know, vicious aliens.

512
00:22:47,896 --> 00:22:50,057
We have really smart and really stupid aliens.

513
00:22:50,057 --> 00:22:52,658
You know, so they're kind of building this boundary,

514
00:22:52,658 --> 00:22:54,818
but they're all still in the same dimensions, you know,

515
00:22:54,818 --> 00:22:55,719
humans are built out of.

516
00:22:55,719 --> 00:22:57,959
So really, both of these things are kind of, I think,

517
00:22:57,959 --> 00:22:59,420
a window into humanity.

518
00:22:59,420 --> 00:23:01,640
And as we, you know, look at imagined aliens,

519
00:23:01,640 --> 00:23:03,221
and as we build robots,

520
00:23:03,221 --> 00:23:06,462
we're actually coming to understand ourselves more thoroughly.

521
00:23:06,462 --> 00:23:08,543
Now, the idea of aliens isn't really new.

522
00:23:08,543 --> 00:23:10,543
You know, there are examples from way back in art

523
00:23:10,543 --> 00:23:12,524
of things that they might have called demons or angels.

524
00:23:13,872 --> 00:23:16,213
More recently, there were a few sightings in the 1800s.

525
00:23:16,213 --> 00:23:19,454
There were these things that they saw during World War II called Foo Fighters.

526
00:23:19,454 --> 00:23:22,495
But it was really after the advent of nuclear weapons

527
00:23:22,495 --> 00:23:26,036
that the kind of whole modern alien craze started.

528
00:23:26,036 --> 00:23:28,197
The Roswell Incident seems to be like ground zero

529
00:23:28,197 --> 00:23:33,438
for where a lot of the kind of modern mythology around aliens spread.

530
00:23:33,755 --> 00:23:39,279
And initially, you know, these aliens were things that were probably very hostile, probably going to come and hurt us.

531
00:23:39,279 --> 00:23:40,040
They were scary.

532
00:23:40,040 --> 00:23:45,824
In some sense, I think they were a personification of this power that we suddenly had to destroy ourselves.

533
00:23:45,824 --> 00:23:48,807
In other contexts, they were also this yearning for adult supervision.

534
00:23:48,807 --> 00:23:53,450
You know, we were hoping that somebody out there was smarter than us and might actually come and help save ourselves.

535
00:23:53,730 --> 00:23:58,014
or even provide an example that maybe we can survive this period in our time.

536
00:23:58,014 --> 00:24:03,278
And this is just one kind of cultural response to kind of this sudden ability to destroy humanity.

537
00:24:03,278 --> 00:24:04,859
Different cultures had different responses.

538
00:24:04,859 --> 00:24:07,661
In Japan, it was Godzilla, which is a little bit different.

539
00:24:07,661 --> 00:24:11,644
It was more of a personification of what would nature say if she could see us doing this.

540
00:24:11,644 --> 00:24:14,246
And so Godzilla was kind of like the revenge of nature, you know, after we had been...

541
00:24:14,347 --> 00:24:18,150
playing with these weapons. But the aliens, in fact, weren't like Godzilla.

542
00:24:18,150 --> 00:24:21,673
They were very vulnerable. We could almost empathize with them. What made them powerful

543
00:24:21,673 --> 00:24:25,416
was their technology. And that was something we could aspire to. We could aspire to become

544
00:24:25,416 --> 00:24:28,759
these gods, which also made them very different than, like, the old Greek and Roman gods that

545
00:24:28,759 --> 00:24:31,742
we could not aspire to become. Okay, so back to the research.

546
00:24:31,742 --> 00:24:37,167
We covered innovation, project risks,

547
00:24:37,733 --> 00:24:39,694
is something that you really have to take seriously.

548
00:24:39,694 --> 00:24:40,854
You know, at every stage of the project,

549
00:24:40,854 --> 00:24:43,135
all the way from beginning to end,

550
00:24:43,135 --> 00:24:45,315
I divide most of the risks that I think of

551
00:24:45,315 --> 00:24:46,396
into these categories,

552
00:24:46,396 --> 00:24:49,537
technology, design, production, marketing, political.

553
00:24:49,537 --> 00:24:51,578
I'm lucky that most of the ideas that I want to do,

554
00:24:51,578 --> 00:24:53,098
you know, I have a freer path.

555
00:24:53,098 --> 00:24:53,958
I think most people here

556
00:24:53,958 --> 00:24:55,319
that have a really cool, innovative idea,

557
00:24:55,319 --> 00:24:56,779
you know, one of the very first battles

558
00:24:56,779 --> 00:24:58,620
they're going to be fighting is the political battle.

559
00:24:58,620 --> 00:25:00,981
How do you get a green light inside your company?

560
00:25:00,981 --> 00:25:02,141
Electronic arts, it actually,

561
00:25:02,141 --> 00:25:03,702
I found it's a very simple trick.

562
00:25:03,702 --> 00:25:06,363
It turns out that all the execs play Worlds of Warcraft.

563
00:25:07,397 --> 00:25:11,200
And so all you have to do is say, oh, it's going to be like World of Warcraft,

564
00:25:11,200 --> 00:25:15,103
except it starts in a tide pool and you end up in space,

565
00:25:15,103 --> 00:25:17,505
and it's not quite multiplayer, but it works.

566
00:25:17,505 --> 00:25:21,568
Yeah.

567
00:25:21,568 --> 00:25:26,051
So, the top risks I saw for Spore, you know, in sorted order,

568
00:25:26,051 --> 00:25:28,773
were the generative animation system,

569
00:25:28,773 --> 00:25:32,116
editor usability, design scope of the project,

570
00:25:32,116 --> 00:25:34,137
quality content, and content pipeline.

571
00:25:34,672 --> 00:25:36,893
Two of these are technology risks, you know,

572
00:25:36,893 --> 00:25:38,294
which kind of involve one approach.

573
00:25:38,294 --> 00:25:39,534
Two of these were design risks.

574
00:25:39,534 --> 00:25:42,196
And the last one was really kind of a production risk.

575
00:25:42,196 --> 00:25:44,897
So what you really want to do in this case

576
00:25:44,897 --> 00:25:47,459
is front-load the team, get the very first core members

577
00:25:47,459 --> 00:25:50,060
in positions to solve those early risks.

578
00:25:50,060 --> 00:25:53,222
I knew that if we couldn't do the generative animation system,

579
00:25:53,222 --> 00:25:55,664
that the whole idea was sunk.

580
00:25:55,664 --> 00:25:59,286
And so one of the very first people I brought on the project

581
00:25:59,286 --> 00:26:00,206
was a guy named Case 1 Pushkin,

582
00:26:00,206 --> 00:26:00,647
who, people know him.

583
00:26:01,840 --> 00:26:02,501
He's a great guy.

584
00:26:02,501 --> 00:26:04,483
And he was like my deep researcher.

585
00:26:04,483 --> 00:26:06,726
And he actually, I had him look at all the procedural

586
00:26:06,726 --> 00:26:08,928
or generative systems out there.

587
00:26:10,152 --> 00:26:11,253
You know, we found some really cool examples.

588
00:26:11,253 --> 00:26:12,694
They were very hard to use,

589
00:26:12,694 --> 00:26:14,876
but they kind of gave us some indication

590
00:26:14,876 --> 00:26:15,737
of the direction to go.

591
00:26:15,737 --> 00:26:17,439
Later, we had Ken Perlin come in

592
00:26:17,439 --> 00:26:18,660
and do some consulting on it,

593
00:26:18,660 --> 00:26:20,722
you know, showing his stuff, his generative stuff.

594
00:26:20,722 --> 00:26:22,783
And then later, Chris Hecker

595
00:26:22,783 --> 00:26:24,525
is now kind of building the tool out for animators.

596
00:26:24,525 --> 00:26:26,867
And so, basically, it was getting

597
00:26:26,867 --> 00:26:28,328
a very qualified team of specialists

598
00:26:28,328 --> 00:26:29,269
to come in and attack that risk.

599
00:26:29,269 --> 00:26:31,731
And I find that these risks are best attacked

600
00:26:31,731 --> 00:26:33,553
with a very small number of very sharp people.

601
00:26:33,713 --> 00:26:36,195
rather than a giant team of kind of more average people,

602
00:26:36,195 --> 00:26:37,676
in which case they'll never solve it.

603
00:26:37,676 --> 00:26:40,058
But the very tightly focused team usually can,

604
00:26:40,058 --> 00:26:41,419
especially if you say,

605
00:26:41,419 --> 00:26:43,000
I don't think you can solve this, there's no way,

606
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:43,981
and make it a challenge for them.

607
00:26:43,981 --> 00:26:46,003
Now, the Polynesian content,

608
00:26:46,003 --> 00:26:47,524
that was something where

609
00:26:47,524 --> 00:26:49,465
we actually had a lot of experience to draw from.

610
00:26:49,465 --> 00:26:51,147
We have these Sims websites,

611
00:26:51,147 --> 00:26:54,429
and a lot of fans are uploading stuff to our Sims website

612
00:26:54,429 --> 00:26:56,231
and sharing it and tracking the creators

613
00:26:56,231 --> 00:26:57,252
and the popularity and stuff.

614
00:26:57,587 --> 00:27:01,309
So I brought over two of the people that actually had architected that system,

615
00:27:01,309 --> 00:27:05,751
Kelshawn and Colin Andrews, to run the pollinated content side.

616
00:27:05,751 --> 00:27:06,211
Yeah, they're great.

617
00:27:06,211 --> 00:27:09,873
And they, in fact, started building prototypes very early on of this system

618
00:27:09,873 --> 00:27:13,815
and capturing all the stuff that we were in development, making in the editors,

619
00:27:13,815 --> 00:27:17,277
and starting to sort it and aesthetically figure out what the categories were.

620
00:27:17,277 --> 00:27:17,417
And...

621
00:27:18,014 --> 00:27:19,956
The fact that they got that prototype going so early

622
00:27:19,956 --> 00:27:22,780
lowered that as a risk factor tremendously right off the bat.

623
00:27:22,780 --> 00:27:24,962
You know, whereas the generative animation system

624
00:27:24,962 --> 00:27:26,985
was kind of a long, ongoing battle that we kept fighting,

625
00:27:26,985 --> 00:27:29,227
and it kind of stayed at the top of the list for a long time.

626
00:27:29,227 --> 00:27:31,810
Design scope, you know, games used to be, like,

627
00:27:31,810 --> 00:27:33,693
about that complex, you know, back in the 80s or so.

628
00:27:33,693 --> 00:27:35,575
Uh, now they're more like this.

629
00:27:36,095 --> 00:27:39,458
And so I knew that I wanted to do a game across all these different scales,

630
00:27:39,458 --> 00:27:42,660
and I kind of reasoned that, well, if I didn't make any one of those scales too complicated,

631
00:27:42,660 --> 00:27:47,824
the whole set of them still would maybe be about the same complexity as a modern game.

632
00:27:47,824 --> 00:27:51,147
And so that was, like, kind of step one for mitigating the design risk.

633
00:27:51,147 --> 00:27:54,610
Another one was bringing in, again, people that

634
00:27:54,610 --> 00:27:55,310
Jason Schenkel

635
00:27:55,949 --> 00:27:57,630
was the lead programmer for Sim Wars,

636
00:27:57,630 --> 00:27:58,590
which is a project that we worked on,

637
00:27:58,590 --> 00:27:59,770
but we never released.

638
00:27:59,770 --> 00:28:01,171
But Jason did a huge number of prototypes

639
00:28:01,171 --> 00:28:03,231
of planetary ecosystems and whatnot

640
00:28:03,231 --> 00:28:04,032
that we drew from.

641
00:28:04,032 --> 00:28:04,972
And so his experience,

642
00:28:04,972 --> 00:28:05,992
he was actually, like,

643
00:28:05,992 --> 00:28:07,593
the first prototyper on Sporb.

644
00:28:07,593 --> 00:28:10,093
Uh, then playing a lot of old games

