00:46:31,511 --> 00:46:33,692
And this is in spaceships colonizing whatever.

1026
00:46:33,692 --> 00:46:38,255
So from this, you know, I kind of played with a lot of parameters around this model.

1027
00:46:38,255 --> 00:46:41,636
And I kind of came to the conclusion that the most probable galactic states we would

1028
00:46:41,636 --> 00:46:45,679
encounter would be either a lifeless galaxy, like at the beginning, one that had a lot

1029
00:46:45,679 --> 00:46:48,820
of microbial life spread through pan-spermia, or a lot of intelligent life.

1030
00:46:48,820 --> 00:46:53,983
And the transitions between these phases would be relatively rapid, especially between the

1031
00:46:53,983 --> 00:46:54,503
last two.

1032
00:46:55,938 --> 00:47:00,981
So, the rear-Earth thing kind of says that there might be all these preconditions that make it special.

1033
00:47:00,981 --> 00:47:03,822
A high-middle star, being in the solar habitable zone,

1034
00:47:03,822 --> 00:47:06,764
having the Moon to help stabilize our planet, Jupiter, the galactic habitable zone.

1035
00:47:06,764 --> 00:47:10,125
These last three things really bought us four billion years of stability,

1036
00:47:10,125 --> 00:47:13,027
which is a remarkably long period of time for one planet to be stable.

1037
00:47:13,027 --> 00:47:16,508
This also kind of bears on what's known as the anthropic principle.

1038
00:47:16,508 --> 00:47:19,330
This is kind of the idea that...

1039
00:47:19,694 --> 00:47:25,499
It's hard for us to infer from where we are how improbable the string of events was required to create us.

1040
00:47:25,499 --> 00:47:28,021
You know, if we're required as observers to ask the question.

1041
00:47:28,021 --> 00:47:32,225
So we wouldn't be here to ask the question unless those million improbable things happened.

1042
00:47:32,225 --> 00:47:33,766
It might be common, it might be improbable.

1043
00:47:33,766 --> 00:47:35,387
We just cannot make a determination about it.

1044
00:47:35,387 --> 00:47:38,129
So we cannot assume that we are common elements in the universe.

1045
00:47:38,129 --> 00:47:42,913
Which is kind of against the prevailing Copernican principle that had been around for several hundred years before that.

1046
00:47:43,074 --> 00:47:45,977
Possible answers to the Fermi Paradox involve things like quarantine,

1047
00:47:45,977 --> 00:47:48,099
the prime director from Star Trek, you know, let's not upset the natives.

1048
00:47:48,099 --> 00:47:51,002
Maybe they're hiding from us. Maybe the galaxy is a very dangerous place

1049
00:47:51,002 --> 00:47:52,524
and they don't want anybody to know where they are.

1050
00:47:52,524 --> 00:47:54,606
Maybe we're looking in the wrong place.

1051
00:47:54,606 --> 00:47:56,729
Maybe they don't use radio waves, they use tachyons,

1052
00:47:56,729 --> 00:47:58,450
or something we can't detect right now.

1053
00:47:59,071 --> 00:48:01,752
Or maybe they don't spread, don't colonize.

1054
00:48:01,752 --> 00:48:07,214
But each one of these arguments kind of assumes that the aliens are applying one strategy.

1055
00:48:07,214 --> 00:48:10,355
And if anything we've learned from studying human history,

1056
00:48:10,355 --> 00:48:13,836
is that humans tend to spread and diversify in their behavior.

1057
00:48:13,836 --> 00:48:16,357
And with the distances involved in interstellar travel,

1058
00:48:16,357 --> 00:48:20,158
there's no way to maintain like a federation or enforce the prime directive.

1059
00:48:20,158 --> 00:48:24,140
So, it seems unlikely to me that any of these things really are good answers to the Fermi Paradox.

1060
00:48:24,140 --> 00:48:25,580
Okay, back to research.

