1177
00:52:45,445 --> 00:52:50,149
2001 was really interesting from a research point of view in that how he got space right.

1178
00:52:50,149 --> 00:52:55,833
Unlike almost every other science fiction even since then, you know, every single scene you were dealing with gravity.

1179
00:52:55,833 --> 00:53:00,157
There was no cheat for gravity where everybody is magically walking on the floor because the gravity generator.

1180
00:53:00,157 --> 00:53:03,399
All the space scenes were totally soundless because in fact there is no sound in space,

1181
00:53:03,399 --> 00:53:06,202
even though you hear TIE fighters and things making noises as they fly by.

1182
00:53:06,828 --> 00:53:09,349
He did background research on human anthropology,

1183
00:53:09,349 --> 00:53:11,411
interviewed people at NASA,

1184
00:53:11,411 --> 00:53:15,113
the kind of plans that they were building for moon bases and space stations,

1185
00:53:15,113 --> 00:53:17,594
and artificial intelligence experts as to what, you know,

1186
00:53:17,594 --> 00:53:20,336
a smart computer of the future might look like and how it might be used.

1187
00:53:20,336 --> 00:53:23,958
Even this scene where, like, Dave gets blasted in with no air

1188
00:53:23,958 --> 00:53:25,739
through the vacuum to turn on the pod,

1189
00:53:25,739 --> 00:53:28,260
he had read a research paper that the Air Force was doing.

1190
00:53:28,260 --> 00:53:29,121
I don't know why they were doing this,

1191
00:53:29,121 --> 00:53:32,203
but they were seeing how long monkeys could survive in a vacuum.

1192
00:53:32,570 --> 00:53:35,411
and they found that they can survive for about a minute, actually with no permanent damage.

1193
00:53:35,411 --> 00:53:39,574
And so he actually based this scene on how long a human could probably survive in a vacuum,

1194
00:53:39,574 --> 00:53:41,575
you know, to turn the airlock knob back on.

1195
00:53:41,575 --> 00:53:44,137
They were also pretty innovative in terms of marketing.

1196
00:53:44,137 --> 00:53:45,818
This is the original poster for 2001.

1197
00:53:45,818 --> 00:53:48,939
And they found at some point, this came out in 1967,

1198
00:53:48,939 --> 00:53:52,281
that a lot of college students were dropping acid and going to see the movie,

1199
00:53:52,281 --> 00:53:53,922
you know, for all the cool visuals and stuff.

1200
00:53:53,922 --> 00:53:55,744
So they redesigned the poster.

1201
00:53:55,744 --> 00:53:59,586
You might notice they changed the tagline as well.

1202
00:54:01,763 --> 00:54:06,965
He did this in conjunction with Arthur C. Clarke, which is one of my favorite science fiction authors.

1203
00:54:06,965 --> 00:54:09,866
And Arthur C. Clarke was similar in that he did a lot of research for his books.

1204
00:54:09,866 --> 00:54:12,667
And his books were almost like a combination of fact and fiction,

1205
00:54:12,667 --> 00:54:17,248
which is kind of a really interesting gray area, especially for researching the kinds of things we do.

1206
00:54:17,248 --> 00:54:21,410
There's a very interesting group of books called world-building books

1207
00:54:21,410 --> 00:54:26,992
that people use to create fantasy environments for role-playing games or science fiction writing.

1208
00:54:26,992 --> 00:54:30,593
There are some very good websites out there, very good resources that have this as well.

1209
00:54:31,073 --> 00:54:35,577
And Wikipedia just continually gets more valuable to me every day,

1210
00:54:35,577 --> 00:54:38,719
primarily because it's filling in the gaps in these research areas.

1211
00:54:38,719 --> 00:54:43,463
It's not really clear whether you're going to find a book about this or a film or what.

1212
00:54:43,463 --> 00:54:47,807
Wikipedia is a great kind of filling in the gaps research resource.

1213
00:54:47,807 --> 00:54:48,107
Oh! Okay.

1214
00:54:48,107 --> 00:54:55,553
I didn't get a chance to do this last year.

1215
00:54:55,553 --> 00:54:56,594
It was too busy.

1216
00:54:57,934 --> 00:55:01,156
But, yeah, this is totally off topic, by the way.

1217
00:55:01,156 --> 00:55:04,658
I mean, this is as off topic as you can get.

1218
00:55:04,658 --> 00:55:05,798
And I love this picture.

1219
00:55:05,798 --> 00:55:08,480
It's like they're going out for a church picnic,

1220
00:55:08,480 --> 00:55:10,721
except they're going to launch a rocket.

1221
00:55:10,721 --> 00:55:12,382
Let's go launch a rocket today.

1222
00:55:12,382 --> 00:55:12,802
Okay.

1223
00:55:12,802 --> 00:55:14,963
I'm going to tell you the story of the Soyuz 23

1224
00:55:14,963 --> 00:55:17,124
that was launched in 1976.

1225
00:55:17,124 --> 00:55:19,085
Cosmonauts Zudov and Rozhdestvsky.

1226
00:55:19,085 --> 00:55:22,067
These were actually military cosmonauts.

1227
00:55:22,067 --> 00:55:22,927
Special...

1228
00:55:23,438 --> 00:55:28,922
core that was trained going up. The Soviets had the very first space station, the Salyut

1229
00:55:28,922 --> 00:55:33,426
series, and they launched six of these. These were scientific space stations, or so we thought.

1230
00:55:33,426 --> 00:55:36,348
It turned out that they had a military space station program as well, and they couldn't

1231
00:55:36,348 --> 00:55:40,051
hide the launches from us, so they just said, oh, we have six Salyuts. But it turned out

1232
00:55:40,051 --> 00:55:44,374
that every other one was, in fact, not a Salyut at all, but an Almaz station, the military

1233
00:55:44,374 --> 00:55:48,557
station. And they were interleaved, the launches. And it was a great deception, and we didn't

1234
00:55:48,557 --> 00:55:50,938
find out until, like, 20 years later about these things.

1235
00:55:51,518 --> 00:55:55,344
The Almaz were interesting. They were basically manned spy satellites.

1236
00:55:55,344 --> 00:55:57,226
They had these huge, you know, telescopes

1237
00:55:57,226 --> 00:55:59,309
that the cosmonauts could point as they were flying over

1238
00:55:59,309 --> 00:56:02,413
and photograph whatever ground control wanted photographed.

1239
00:56:03,023 --> 00:56:05,524
At the same time, the US was developing the US Dynastar X-20

1240
00:56:05,524 --> 00:56:12,106
as this kind of re-entry vehicle that maybe could be used as an interceptor in the Russian slot.

1241
00:56:12,106 --> 00:56:17,048
And so they were convinced that if we found out that they had manned spy satellites,

1242
00:56:17,048 --> 00:56:19,129
that we would go up and shoot them down.

1243
00:56:19,129 --> 00:56:21,490
So they decided they had to defend this thing.

1244
00:56:21,490 --> 00:56:23,811
Now witness the firepower of this fully armed and operational battle station.

1245
00:56:24,457 --> 00:56:27,860
So in fact, these were the first armed battle stations in orbit.

1246
00:56:27,860 --> 00:56:30,583
They were armed with 20mm anti-aircraft cannons

1247
00:56:30,583 --> 00:56:33,926
that were bore-sided along the length of the space station.

1248
00:56:33,926 --> 00:56:36,368
They actually, you know, destroyed several targets in target practice,

1249
00:56:36,368 --> 00:56:38,250
you know, satellites at about a mile distance,

1250
00:56:38,250 --> 00:56:39,891
but it was terrifying to fire because

1251
00:56:39,891 --> 00:56:43,374
it had to be tied into the reaction control system of the space station,

1252
00:56:43,374 --> 00:56:46,057
otherwise they would de-orbit the station with the recoil of the gun.

1253
00:56:46,057 --> 00:56:48,499
So, they were pretty risky.

1254
00:56:49,135 --> 00:56:55,179
So these guys pull up in their Soyuz, but the approach computer has them like almost crashing into it, going way too fast.

1255
00:56:55,179 --> 00:56:57,941
They didn't trust it, so they shut it off and they did a back burn and all this.

1256
00:56:57,941 --> 00:56:59,402
And before they knew it, they'd wasted all their fuel.

1257
00:56:59,402 --> 00:57:03,025
They didn't have any more fuel to do a manual docking, so they had to abort the mission at that point.

1258
00:57:03,025 --> 00:57:04,806
They never got to dock with the Almaz.

1259
00:57:04,806 --> 00:57:09,309
So they're coming back, and Mission Control sends them the wrong coordinates for reentry,

1260
00:57:09,309 --> 00:57:12,712
and they end up coming in like a hundred kilometers off target.

1261
00:57:13,058 --> 00:57:16,403
That puts them right in the path, right in the middle of this giant blizzard

1262
00:57:16,403 --> 00:57:18,086
that's blowing through Kazakhstan at the time.

1263
00:57:18,086 --> 00:57:20,950
And the blizzard pushes them another 50 kilometers off target.

1264
00:57:21,461 --> 00:57:25,782
and they end up coming down into scenic Lake Tengiz, right in the middle of it,

1265
00:57:25,782 --> 00:57:31,444
except it's not so scenic because it's like a blizzard and it's 20 degrees below zero at this point,

1266
00:57:31,444 --> 00:57:36,006
and they hit the ice and break through the ice of this frozen lake and start to sink,

1267
00:57:36,006 --> 00:57:39,547
and the parachute drags the whole Soyuz capsule upside down,

1268
00:57:39,547 --> 00:57:44,788
and now these guys are stuck in their spacesuits upside down, bopping up and down in a storm,

1269
00:57:44,788 --> 00:57:46,389
and this is when it starts getting bad.

1270
00:57:48,961 --> 00:57:50,862
The inside of one of these Soyuz is like the inside of an old VW.

1271
00:57:50,862 --> 00:57:53,164
And they're wearing spacesuits. They can't really...

1272
00:57:53,164 --> 00:57:55,806
They've never been able to take off the spacesuits while in that capsule.

1273
00:57:55,806 --> 00:57:57,548
So they had to cut them off with knives.

1274
00:57:57,548 --> 00:57:59,029
And there was an air vent that opened

1275
00:57:59,029 --> 00:58:02,632
because they assumed that they'd be sitting on the ground and they didn't need air.

1276
00:58:02,632 --> 00:58:03,973
And then water was rushing in the capsule at this point.

1277
00:58:03,973 --> 00:58:08,216
And so they were scrambling, grabbed the rags, managed to plug the hole to stop the leak.

1278
00:58:08,216 --> 00:58:10,798
And at this point, they were also out of air

1279
00:58:10,798 --> 00:58:13,320
because they, you know, the air vent was open and let air in.

1280
00:58:13,821 --> 00:58:18,950
One of the guys happened to be a diver, and so he knew that the real danger was the carbon dioxide poisoning.

1281
00:58:18,950 --> 00:58:23,117
And so they had almost no battery life left. They turned off every system, including the radio beacon.

1282
00:58:23,596 --> 00:58:26,377
to find them and he stayed up all night

1283
00:58:26,377 --> 00:58:28,878
bobbing upside down in the water and he,

1284
00:58:28,878 --> 00:58:30,858
right before he passed out from the CO2 poisoning,

1285
00:58:30,858 --> 00:58:32,419
he would turn on the CO2 scrubber

1286
00:58:32,419 --> 00:58:33,779
just long enough to get clear-headed again

1287
00:58:33,779 --> 00:58:35,360
and then turn it back off to save the battery power

1288
00:58:35,360 --> 00:58:37,241
and basically stayed all night doing that.

1289
00:58:37,241 --> 00:58:39,221
And the next day, he cleared a little bit

1290
00:58:39,221 --> 00:58:41,182
and an intrepid helicopter pilot saw the part

1291
00:58:41,182 --> 00:58:43,143
of the parachute cable sticking out of the ice,

1292
00:58:43,143 --> 00:58:44,283
managed to hook it with the helicopter

1293
00:58:44,283 --> 00:58:45,984
and drag them like five kilometers to the shoreline.

1294
00:58:45,984 --> 00:58:48,084
And to their amazement, when they opened the capsule,

1295
00:58:48,084 --> 00:58:49,985
both cosmonauts were still alive.

1296
00:58:49,985 --> 00:58:51,085
So this one has a happy ending.

1297
00:58:51,085 --> 00:58:52,666
That's the Russian Space Minute.

1298
00:58:59,650 --> 00:59:00,511
So back to the research.

1299
00:59:00,511 --> 00:59:03,613
When we do research, one of the other things we want to do

1300
00:59:03,613 --> 00:59:07,375
is establish kind of what is the style, texture of the world?

1301
00:59:07,375 --> 00:59:10,116
And this is almost more in a visual kinesthetic sense.

1302
00:59:10,116 --> 00:59:10,797
Is it real?

1303
00:59:10,797 --> 00:59:11,477
Is it toy-like?

1304
00:59:11,477 --> 00:59:12,898
How familiar does it feel?

1305
00:59:12,898 --> 00:59:14,419
Is it a caricature?

1306
00:59:14,419 --> 00:59:16,920
In sport, we actually very early identified this kind of split

1307
00:59:16,920 --> 00:59:19,802
in our team, kind of between what we call the science

1308
00:59:19,802 --> 00:59:23,184
team and the cute team, in terms of how should this thing look?

1309
00:59:23,184 --> 00:59:25,385
And these are kind of representative samples

1310
00:59:25,385 --> 00:59:26,046
from both teams.

1311
00:59:27,666 --> 00:59:30,627
Uh, we eventually decided that we really, whenever possible,

1312
00:59:30,627 --> 00:59:33,367
wanted the players to be able to make that choice themselves in the editors.

1313
00:59:33,367 --> 00:59:35,668
And we tried to make the editors fairly malleable,

1314
00:59:35,668 --> 00:59:38,088
and that would be the primary dimension that they were kind of exploring.

1315
00:59:38,088 --> 00:59:41,309
Um, some of the research material spanned both of these things.

1316
00:59:41,309 --> 00:59:42,870
We kind of went from fairly realistic stuff.

1317
00:59:42,870 --> 00:59:43,970
This is the work of Dougal Dixon,

1318
00:59:43,970 --> 00:59:47,231
who does a lot of kind of imaginary zoology stuff.

1319
00:59:47,231 --> 00:59:49,911
He actually also later worked on the series The Future is Wild

1320
00:59:49,911 --> 00:59:51,852
for the Discovery Channel, which was an excellent series

1321
00:59:51,852 --> 00:59:53,372
about maybe the future of evolution on Earth.

1322
00:59:54,500 --> 00:59:56,382
More imaginative stuff, we found great sources.

1323
00:59:56,382 --> 01:00:00,384
Disney did these series of movies with NASA back in the 50s about space.

1324
01:00:00,384 --> 01:00:03,126
And their animators were imagining what life on Mars might look like.

1325
01:00:03,126 --> 01:00:05,907
This is a great movie. I don't know if any of y'all saw this movie.

1326
01:00:05,907 --> 01:00:09,690
It had these really imaginative plans and things.

1327
01:00:09,690 --> 01:00:12,992
And it was like this French, Czechoslovakian, weird animated thing.

1328
01:00:12,992 --> 01:00:15,873
But still, the creatures and things in there were great.

1329
01:00:15,873 --> 01:00:18,815
As far as vehicles, you know, this is, like, great, Thunderbirds.

1330
01:00:18,815 --> 01:00:19,836
You know, these toy-like feel.

1331
01:00:19,836 --> 01:00:24,178
It turns out that Thunderbird 1 was actually based upon the Soyuz launcher, by the way.

1332
01:00:25,527 --> 01:00:28,649
And then these things, which I showed a little bit of last year,

1333
01:00:28,649 --> 01:00:32,531
these comic book covers, and these are definitely going more in the cute kind of caricature direction.

1334
01:00:32,531 --> 01:00:35,933
And it was just amazing how many of these things I managed to dig up.

1335
01:00:35,933 --> 01:00:38,935
And each one of these is several years' worth of issues.

1336
01:00:38,935 --> 01:00:42,537
Future, future, Captain Future, Man of Tomorrow, Tales of Wonder, Uncanny.

1337
01:00:42,537 --> 01:00:43,697
They just go on and on.

1338
01:00:43,697 --> 01:00:48,720
And each one of these things has this interesting combination of an interesting world,

1339
01:00:48,720 --> 01:00:50,821
maybe some cool vehicles, some aliens.

1340
01:00:50,821 --> 01:00:53,903
Exactly the stuff that we wanted to have in our game.

1341
01:00:54,555 --> 01:00:58,561
My animation director, Bob King, actually did a couple for us,

1342
01:00:58,561 --> 01:01:00,263
kind of in that style,

1343
01:01:00,263 --> 01:01:05,329
just to get a sense of what that would feel like.

1344
01:01:05,988 --> 01:01:11,875
It always helps to actually get like a real sample that's relevant to what you're doing, you know, in that style, and it really helps you kind of visualize it.

1345
01:01:11,875 --> 01:01:16,100
Um, this is actually the very first box I designed for Spore way, way back.

1346
01:01:16,100 --> 01:01:18,442
You know, one of the first things I always do when I do a game is I design a box.

1347
01:01:18,442 --> 01:01:24,990
And I was trying to give people a sense for what I was thinking, and it's, what I'm thinking has changed a lot since then, but this is kind of my original title and name for it.

1348
01:01:25,070 --> 01:01:26,250
This is the back of the box.

1349
01:01:26,250 --> 01:01:28,391
And so I do the back of the box with bullet points,

1350
01:01:28,391 --> 01:01:29,832
little screenshots, you know.

1351
01:01:29,832 --> 01:01:31,173
And in fact, I put this on a real box

1352
01:01:31,173 --> 01:01:32,833
with something inside of it so it feels heavy

1353
01:01:32,833 --> 01:01:34,714
so I can hand it to somebody and they can imagine,

1354
01:01:34,714 --> 01:01:36,235
oh, yeah, I'm in a software store holding this.

1355
01:01:36,235 --> 01:01:38,076
Would I buy it?

1356
01:01:38,076 --> 01:01:40,077
If you zoom in here, you'll see that this is early on

1357
01:01:40,077 --> 01:01:42,538
when I was thinking that we would be colonizing

1358
01:01:42,538 --> 01:01:44,819
at sublight velocities and how exciting that would be.

1359
01:01:44,819 --> 01:01:45,579
I kind of changed my mind.

1360
01:01:45,579 --> 01:01:48,461
These are the system requirements

1361
01:01:48,461 --> 01:01:50,101
that I was estimating at the time.

1362
01:01:59,637 --> 01:02:04,039
Now, you know, early in this phase, we wanted to go through this process of deconstruction

1363
01:02:04,039 --> 01:02:09,082
and reconstruction of creatures, vehicles, buildings, planets, all the stuff in the game.

1364
01:02:09,082 --> 01:02:12,243
We actually had a lot of people come in and say, draw an alien creature. If you could

1365
01:02:12,243 --> 01:02:15,445
design a creature in the game, what would it be? And we had them do drawings. And we

1366
01:02:15,445 --> 01:02:19,867
studied the drawings. More recently, our fan sites have started doing that. This is what

1367
01:02:19,867 --> 01:02:22,829
I want to build in Spore. These are from one of our fans, Hydro Mancer.

1368
01:02:23,525 --> 01:02:26,586
These are drawings that he's done of things that he wants to do in the game.

1369
01:02:26,586 --> 01:02:29,747
And it's really instructive for us to go look at those expectations and say,

1370
01:02:29,747 --> 01:02:31,928
can we measure our editors against this?

1371
01:02:31,928 --> 01:02:35,589
This is actually a really cool little prototype that appeared,

1372
01:02:35,589 --> 01:02:37,390
I think, after we showed Spore last year at GDC.

1373
01:02:37,390 --> 01:02:40,912
These students at USC took their first level, the cell level,

1374
01:02:40,912 --> 01:02:43,453
and built it, basically, you know, in Flash.

1375
01:02:43,453 --> 01:02:45,153
A very cool game.

1376
01:02:45,153 --> 01:02:48,014
And it's great when other people do your prototypes for free,

1377
01:02:48,014 --> 01:02:50,515
you know, without even asking like that.

1378
01:02:50,945 --> 01:02:56,010
I got to meet Jenova Chin just like two days ago, and he's a brilliant guy with a great aesthetic.

1379
01:02:56,010 --> 01:02:58,492
We also hired this conceptual artist, Christian Schur, who came in,

1380
01:02:58,492 --> 01:03:02,356
and we had him draw all sorts of things that we then went through this deconstructive process with.

1381
01:03:02,356 --> 01:03:08,281
We had him draw things in different styles, like scary aliens, maybe goofy things.

1382
01:03:09,107 --> 01:03:11,629
you know, other things that were just kind of odd and alien-like ways.

1383
01:03:11,629 --> 01:03:16,512
Um, after taking all these creatures, some of which were related, some of which weren't,

1384
01:03:16,512 --> 01:03:18,153
we then started deconstructing them into parts.

1385
01:03:18,153 --> 01:03:21,636
You know, if we had to pull sets of parts off of these things, what would they be?

1386
01:03:21,636 --> 01:03:25,919
And, um, we found that the eyes and the mouths were like the most expressive parts that we could pull off.

1387
01:03:25,919 --> 01:03:28,160
But then we had all the other ones, hands, wings.

1388
01:03:28,860 --> 01:03:32,402
And then at some point we started putting these deconstructed parts into a taxonomy.

1389
01:03:32,402 --> 01:03:35,904
How do we now sort these parts with some sort of evolutionary relationship?

1390
01:03:35,904 --> 01:03:40,127
You know, what is the path in which a player might explore these on a tech tree, for instance?

1391
01:03:40,127 --> 01:03:41,708
And what is the functional categorization?

1392
01:03:41,708 --> 01:03:43,889
So these might be carnivorous mouths up here.

1393
01:03:43,889 --> 01:03:45,890
These might be herbivorous mouths over there.

1394
01:03:45,890 --> 01:03:48,591
And so we're just getting some sense of how we can kind of take these whole constructs

1395
01:03:48,591 --> 01:03:50,653
and pull them into lower and lower level pieces

1396
01:03:50,653 --> 01:03:52,534
and then establish the relationships between those pieces.

1397
01:03:52,534 --> 01:03:54,915
And then we move them into modeling, you know,

1398
01:03:54,915 --> 01:03:57,136
because it's a big difference going from kind of illustration to modeling.

1399
01:03:57,804 --> 01:03:59,666
And then we start building larger sets of these things

1400
01:03:59,666 --> 01:04:00,647
that we're actually going to use in game.

1401
01:04:00,647 --> 01:04:02,809
Each one of these parts also, by the way, has morph channels.

1402
01:04:02,809 --> 01:04:05,091
So each one represents the center of, in fact,

1403
01:04:05,091 --> 01:04:07,733
a fairly wide morph space where you can stretch the toes out

1404
01:04:07,733 --> 01:04:09,795
or make them curly or add this or that feature to it.

1405
01:04:09,795 --> 01:04:12,097
And then eventually reconstruct features

1406
01:04:12,097 --> 01:04:15,040
after going through that deconstruction-reconstruction process

1407
01:04:15,040 --> 01:04:17,543
that I mentioned with the generative artists,

1408
01:04:17,543 --> 01:04:18,884
doing it with the content here as well.

1409
01:04:18,884 --> 01:04:20,465
Same thing with textures.

1410
01:04:20,815 --> 01:04:24,358
brainstorm ideas, then go out and actually develop the

1411
01:04:24,358 --> 01:04:26,820
particular scripts, apply them, see how close we got to the

1412
01:04:26,820 --> 01:04:27,941
targets.

1413
01:04:27,941 --> 01:04:29,742
Vehicles, pretty much the same thing.

1414
01:04:29,742 --> 01:04:32,604
Conceptual, air, land, sea, build the models, texture,

1415
01:04:32,604 --> 01:04:33,085
buildings.

1416
01:04:34,791 --> 01:04:36,713
Same thing, blocks, models.

1417
01:04:36,713 --> 01:04:39,095
And then finally put them in a scene.

1418
01:04:39,095 --> 01:04:41,217
Planets were a little more elaborate.

1419
01:04:41,217 --> 01:04:44,741
On the planets, we actually started with a lot of very simple descriptions

1420
01:04:44,741 --> 01:04:48,104
of the variety of worlds we wanted players to be able to create in the game.

1421
01:04:48,104 --> 01:04:50,747
We took a few of those and we went really deep on them,

1422
01:04:50,747 --> 01:04:52,549
looking at the materials that we might find on that world,

1423
01:04:52,549 --> 01:04:53,970
how that might influence the coloring,

1424
01:04:53,970 --> 01:04:58,735
what sort of items, vehicles, trees, landforms we might find on those worlds.

1425
01:04:59,483 --> 01:05:02,586
And then developing these kind of pictures showing the world.

1426
01:05:02,586 --> 01:05:06,290
Another process was actually taking worlds and going through and building a backstory.

1427
01:05:06,290 --> 01:05:08,232
What sort of cities would they build?

1428
01:05:08,232 --> 01:05:09,533
What would their industry be?

1429
01:05:09,533 --> 01:05:10,734
What would their sociology be like?

1430
01:05:10,734 --> 01:05:12,435
What are the elements of their technology?

1431
01:05:12,435 --> 01:05:14,337
And so these are all from the same world,

1432
01:05:14,337 --> 01:05:18,741
kind of looking at different snapshots of how these people live and how their world looks.

1433
01:05:18,741 --> 01:05:22,445
And then eventually developing the characters, reassembling it all into one scene.

1434
01:05:23,210 --> 01:05:26,472
for the final rendering. And, you know, it isn't that we want the players to build exactly

1435
01:05:26,472 --> 01:05:31,817
this world. Each one of these worlds represents some outpost of this space, this creative

1436
01:05:31,817 --> 01:05:34,920
space that we want them to be able to build themselves. And so they're like almost eigenvalues

1437
01:05:34,920 --> 01:05:41,325
around the planet space. Now, eventually we get to the geology level and we're actually

1438
01:05:41,325 --> 01:05:45,288
developing scripts that will carve out and make these planets. Some are more fantastic,

1439
01:05:45,288 --> 01:05:46,930
some are more realistic.

1440
01:05:47,668 --> 01:05:50,289
We have one guy, Christian Stratton, who's kind of like my Magrathea.

1441
01:05:50,289 --> 01:05:53,690
This is the guy that builds my planets for me, one of my artists.

1442
01:05:53,690 --> 01:05:58,231
He's actually been building a taxonomy of what types of planets we would find in different zones,

1443
01:05:58,231 --> 01:06:03,372
how they should look, plus their relative distribution in the universe.

1444
01:06:03,372 --> 01:06:06,413
We have some that are very out there, imaginative, more Dr. Seuss,

1445
01:06:06,413 --> 01:06:09,274
that we want to be very rare. If you find one of those, you get excited about it.

1446
01:06:09,274 --> 01:06:12,675
Most of them are more terrestrial, so there is this concept of kind of...

1447
01:06:13,868 --> 01:06:19,273
whimsical equals rarity, that as you're exploring the galaxy, you feel like you've discovered treasures.

1448
01:06:19,273 --> 01:06:21,374
As we pull away from the planets, we get out to all these cool Hubble pictures.

1449
01:06:21,374 --> 01:06:25,778
And we're trying to recreate all these in 3D. These are actually from the game,

1450
01:06:25,778 --> 01:06:31,742
game versions of all the Hubble objects, so they're three-dimensional things that you can kind of move around,

1451
01:06:31,742 --> 01:06:33,063
interact with in space level.

1452
01:06:33,063 --> 01:06:38,067
Now to wind down really quick here...

1453
01:06:38,067 --> 01:06:40,529
Okay, back to Drake's equation.

1454
01:06:40,529 --> 01:06:40,589
Now...

1455
01:06:41,025 --> 01:06:42,906
Clearly all these values are not zero.

1456
01:06:42,906 --> 01:06:45,767
And in fact, none of those values can be zero.

1457
01:06:45,767 --> 01:06:48,228
If any of those values were zero, we wouldn't be here.

1458
01:06:48,228 --> 01:06:49,888
So each one of these values has to be something.

1459
01:06:49,888 --> 01:06:52,369
If we take fairly pessimistic assumptions

1460
01:06:52,369 --> 01:06:54,649
and we bump them all up to .01,

1461
01:06:54,649 --> 01:06:57,650
and most of these are fractional, so it's like 1%,

1462
01:06:57,650 --> 01:06:59,471
and then we just take those numbers

1463
01:06:59,471 --> 01:07:00,771
and we multiply them times the, you know,

1464
01:07:00,771 --> 01:07:03,292
100 billion stars in a typical galaxy

1465
01:07:03,292 --> 01:07:06,213
times the 100 billion galaxies that we know of,

1466
01:07:06,213 --> 01:07:08,414
we still end up with a pretty large number of aliens out there,

1467
01:07:08,414 --> 01:07:09,574
about 100 million in this case.

1468
01:07:10,504 --> 01:07:16,288
That's a large number, but on the other hand, that's only about one alien species per thousand galaxies.

1469
01:07:16,288 --> 01:07:19,431
So even if we bump those numbers up a bit, we're still talking about

1470
01:07:19,431 --> 01:07:25,876
probably less than one alien species per galaxy, especially if they spread into a galaxy very rapidly.

1471
01:07:25,876 --> 01:07:28,798
So my conclusions from SETI, not that you really care,

1472
01:07:28,798 --> 01:07:34,243
is that they're out there, but they're probably really far away, not in our galaxy.

1473
01:07:34,243 --> 01:07:36,484
And that has a lot of implications for the search for SETI,

1474
01:07:36,484 --> 01:07:39,247
that we should be looking further out to distant galaxies.

1475
01:07:39,840 --> 01:07:44,942
My research conclusions are that, and this is something I do always at the beginning of every project,

1476
01:07:44,942 --> 01:07:48,843
is I take a lot of time to consider it, and don't get too committed to any one idea too early.

1477
01:07:48,843 --> 01:07:52,305
And that's what I'm doing a lot of the reading and the research phase.

1478
01:07:52,305 --> 01:07:57,147
I cast usually a very wide net over subjects, and a lot of times, like in the Sims,

1479
01:07:57,147 --> 01:08:01,789
which started as an architectural simulator and led more to behavioral stuff,

1480
01:08:01,789 --> 01:08:05,910
I'll find myself taking very interesting kind of twists and turns through that research path.

1481
01:08:06,596 --> 01:08:09,502
And what you really want to know is what 90% of the material is irrelevant to that core idea,

1482
01:08:09,502 --> 01:08:13,372
because that core idea is going to be shifting around underneath your feet all the time,

1483
01:08:13,372 --> 01:08:16,579
and you need to kind of understand the region of space it can shift in.

1484
01:08:17,191 --> 01:08:19,653
I have no problem with this one.

1485
01:08:19,653 --> 01:08:22,595
But getting totally obsessive about your subject, I find, helps a lot.

1486
01:08:22,595 --> 01:08:23,696
You know, it drives the interest.

1487
01:08:23,696 --> 01:08:27,459
You know, whenever you see anything that's relevant to what you're working on,

1488
01:08:27,459 --> 01:08:28,720
you'll see it more readily on the shelf,

1489
01:08:28,720 --> 01:08:30,301
or somebody mentions something, or an article.

1490
01:08:30,301 --> 01:08:33,443
You'll just find yourself absorbing this stuff so readily

1491
01:08:33,443 --> 01:08:34,504
that it's almost effortless.

1492
01:08:34,504 --> 01:08:38,127
And then you want to cultivate that onto your team, you know,

1493
01:08:38,127 --> 01:08:40,068
as you talk to your team about this stuff, you know,

1494
01:08:40,068 --> 01:08:41,089
and get them interested in it.

1495
01:08:41,089 --> 01:08:43,351
Pretty soon you'll be talking about this stuff over lunch,

1496
01:08:43,351 --> 01:08:45,292
and you're all really enjoying it and learning from each other.

1497
01:08:46,472 --> 01:08:50,034
And this kind of, you know, comes to the fact that eventually you're going to become a teacher.

1498
01:08:50,034 --> 01:08:52,255
Not just to the people on your team, but to the people in your game.

1499
01:08:52,255 --> 01:08:55,457
You know, these deep lessons that you're learning through research

1500
01:08:55,457 --> 01:08:59,379
are eventually, through several filters, going to end up, you know, kind of as a player.

1501
01:08:59,379 --> 01:09:01,780
And this is one thing that is probably the most important to me,

1502
01:09:01,780 --> 01:09:05,742
is the fact that we always have the opportunity to change our players at a very deep level.

1503
01:09:05,742 --> 01:09:09,204
I mean, to the point where we can influence their future career, for instance.

1504
01:09:09,660 --> 01:09:11,842
And that's something that we shouldn't take lightly.

1505
01:09:11,842 --> 01:09:14,865
And it's something that we shouldn't squander.

1506
01:09:14,865 --> 01:09:19,069
So we should probably make the best use of that whenever we can.

1507
01:09:19,069 --> 01:09:19,369
So thank you.

